Perhaps the biggest contribution

The deepest idea running through your work isn’t any individual daemon.

It’s this:

Intelligence can improve by improving the organization of reasoning, not just by increasing the amount of knowledge.

That aligns with a broader principle in AI and cognitive science: performance depends not only on what a system knows, but also on how it retrieves, organizes, composes, and evaluates that knowledge. A framework like the Pantheon aims to provide reusable “mental infrastructure” that helps coordinate those processes over time. Whether it succeeds depends on careful testing and refinement, but that is a coherent architectural objective.